Here’s a high-level walkthrough with code snippets:

1. **Set up a new Svelte project**:
   Use `degit` to quickly scaffold a new Svelte app.
   ```bash
   npx degit sveltejs/template anime-svelte-app
   cd anime-svelte-app
   npm install
   ```

2. **Install Svelte Material UI (SMUI)**:
   We’ll use SMUI for Material UI components.
   ```bash
   npm install --save-dev @smui/button @smui/card @smui/textfield
   ```

3. **Set up GraphQL**: Use the `graphql-request` package to make requests to the AniList API.
   ```bash
   npm install graphql-request
   ```

4. **Create a Svelte component to fetch and display anime**:
   Replace the content of `src/App.svelte` with the following:

```svelte
<script>
  import { onMount } from "svelte";
  import { request, gql } from "graphql-request";
  import Card from "@smui/card";
  import Button from "@smui/button";

  let animeList = [];

  const query = gql`
    query {
      Page(page: 1, perPage: 10) {
        media(type: ANIME, sort: POPULARITY_DESC) {
          title {
            romaji
          }
          averageScore
        }
      }
    }
  `;

  const fetchAnime = async () => {
    try {
      const data = await request("https://graphql.anilist.co", query);
      animeList = data.Page.media.map((anime) => ({
        title: anime.title.romaji,
        rating: anime.averageScore,
      }));
    } catch (error) {
      console.error("Error fetching data:", error);
    }
  };

  onMount(() => {
    fetchAnime();
  });
</script>

<main>
  <h1>Anime Titles and Ratings</h1>
  {#if animeList.length > 0}
    <ul>
      {#each animeList as anime}
        <Card>
          <h2>{anime.title}</h2>
          <p>Rating: {anime.rating}</p>
        </Card>
      {/each}
    </ul>
  {:else}
    <p>Loading...</p>
  {/if}
</main>

<style>
  main {
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 1em;
    max-width: 600px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  Card {
    margin: 1em 0;
    padding: 1em;
  }
</style>
```

5. **Wrap the displayed data in JSON format**:
   To display JSON, you can use `JSON.stringify()` within the `ul` or another element to present the raw data structure.

```svelte
<pre>{JSON.stringify(animeList, null, 2)}</pre>
```

6. **Run your app**:
   Start the local development server to see your app in action.
   ```bash
   npm run dev
   ```

This setup creates a basic Svelte application that fetches and displays anime titles and their ratings from AniList using GraphQL. The JSON output is also displayed for some debugging or deeper insights into the data structure. This approach showcases how to integrate Svelte with Material UI-like components using SMUI and how to interface with external GraphQL APIs.

